<h2 id="safety">Pre-Transfusion Safety: Two-Nurse Verification</h2>
<p>Blood transfusion errors are among the most preventable and deadly patient safety events. The pre-transfusion check requires TWO licensed nurses at the bedside verifying simultaneously:</p>
<ul>
<li>Patient name and date of birth (verbally with patient and on wristband)</li>
<li>Patient blood type and Rh factor on blood product label vs. patient record</li>
<li>Unit number / blood bank ID matches exactly between bag and paperwork</li>
<li>Expiration date of the unit</li>
<li>ABO compatibility between donor unit and recipient</li>
<li>Visual inspection: any clumping, gas bubbles, abnormal color, or broken seal = return to blood bank</li>
</ul>
<div class="danger"><strong>If ANY identifier does not match:</strong> Do NOT transfuse. Return the unit to the blood bank immediately. ABO incompatible transfusion is a fatal error.</div>

<h3>IV Access and Fluid Compatibility</h3>
<ul>
<li>Use 18-gauge or larger IV catheter (smaller gauges damage RBCs)</li>
<li>Use a blood administration set with a 170&ndash;260 micron filter</li>
<li>ONLY normal saline (0.9% NS) is compatible with blood — NEVER dextrose (causes hemolysis) or LR (contains calcium → clots)</li>
<li>Transfuse most products within 4 hours of removal from blood bank refrigerator</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="monitoring">Monitoring During Transfusion</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Time Point</th><th>Action</th><th>Rationale</th></tr>
<tr><td>Before starting</td><td>Baseline vitals (temp, HR, BP, RR, O2 sat, pain, urine color)</td><td>Detect changes during transfusion</td></tr>
<tr><td>First 15 minutes</td><td>Remain at bedside; start slowly (2 mL/min or per policy); recheck vitals at 15 min</td><td>Most severe reactions occur in first 15&ndash;50 mL; early detection = stop before more blood infused</td></tr>
<tr><td>During transfusion</td><td>Vitals q30&ndash;60 min per policy; educate patient to report chills, back/flank pain, itching, SOB, flushing</td><td>Ongoing monitoring for delayed reactions</td></tr>
<tr><td>End of transfusion</td><td>Final vitals; document volume infused and patient response; observe for any delayed symptoms</td><td>Documentation and completeness</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="reactions">Types of Transfusion Reactions</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Reaction</th><th>Mechanism</th><th>Signs &amp; Symptoms</th><th>Onset</th></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Acute Hemolytic (AHTR)</strong></td><td>ABO incompatibility; IgM antibodies destroy RBCs; complement activation</td><td>Fever, chills, back/flank pain (hemolysis = HALLMARK flank pain), hypotension, dark red/brown urine (hemoglobinuria), DIC, acute renal failure, death</td><td>First few mL to first 15 min; immediate</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Febrile Non-Hemolytic (FNHTR)</strong></td><td>Recipient antibodies against donor WBC antigens; cytokines in stored blood</td><td>Fever (&ge;1&deg;C rise from baseline), chills, headache, malaise; NO hemolysis</td><td>During or up to 4 hr after; common</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Mild Allergic</strong></td><td>IgE-mediated response to donor plasma proteins</td><td>Urticaria (hives), itching, flushing; NO systemic symptoms; NO fever</td><td>During transfusion; very common</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Anaphylactic</strong></td><td>IgA-deficient recipient has anti-IgA antibodies reacting to donor IgA</td><td>Bronchospasm, hypotension, angioedema, loss of consciousness; RAPID onset; life-threatening</td><td>First few mL; rapid</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>TRALI</strong> (Transfusion-Related Acute Lung Injury)</td><td>Donor antibodies activate recipient neutrophils → lung injury; non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema</td><td>Acute respiratory distress, hypoxia, bilateral pulmonary infiltrates on CXR within 6 hr; normal or LOW CVP/PCWP (non-cardiogenic); fever, hypotension</td><td>Within 6 hr; usually 1&ndash;2 hr</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>TACO</strong> (Transfusion-Associated Circulatory Overload)</td><td>Fluid overload from too-rapid or too-large volume transfusion</td><td>HTN, tachycardia, dyspnea, crackles, elevated CVP/PCWP, frothy sputum, pulmonary edema; responds to diuretics</td><td>During or up to 6 hr after</td></tr>
<tr><td><strong>Delayed Hemolytic (DHTR)</strong></td><td>Anamnestic antibody response; not detected by pre-transfusion crossmatch</td><td>Unexplained fall in hemoglobin 3&ndash;10 days post-transfusion; mild fever, jaundice</td><td>3&ndash;10 days post-transfusion</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="response">Immediate Nursing Response to ANY Suspected Reaction</h2>
<div class="danger">
<ol>
<li><strong>STOP the transfusion immediately</strong> — disconnect blood tubing at IV site</li>
<li><strong>Maintain IV access</strong> — keep the IV open with 0.9% NS (do NOT let IV go dry)</li>
<li><strong>Notify the provider immediately</strong></li>
<li><strong>Notify the blood bank</strong> — return the blood unit with tubing intact; blood bank will run clerical recheck and repeat crossmatch</li>
<li><strong>Obtain vital signs</strong> and reassess patient</li>
<li><strong>Send blood/urine samples</strong> per facility protocol (urinalysis, repeat type &amp; screen, CBC, DAT)</li>
<li><strong>Document</strong> everything: time started, mL infused, first symptom, actions taken, provider notified</li>
</ol>
</div>

<h3>Reaction-Specific Interventions (after stopping)</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Reaction</th><th>Additional Interventions</th></tr>
<tr><td>AHTR</td><td>Aggressive IV fluids (normal saline) to maintain urine output &ge;100 mL/hr; furosemide to prevent renal failure; dopamine for hypotension; monitor for DIC; kidney support</td></tr>
<tr><td>FNHTR</td><td>Acetaminophen for fever (not aspirin); meperidine for rigors; premedicate with acetaminophen before future transfusions; consider leukoreduced products</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mild Allergic</td><td>Diphenhydramine (Benadryl) IM/IV; may RESTART transfusion slowly after symptoms resolve if ONLY urticaria (per provider order)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Anaphylaxis</td><td>Epinephrine 0.3&ndash;0.5 mg IM (vastus lateralis); airway support; IV fluids; steroids; use washed or IgA-deficient blood products for future transfusions</td></tr>
<tr><td>TRALI</td><td>Oxygen; mechanical ventilation if severe; supportive care; NO diuretics (preload-dependent; not cardiogenic); report to blood bank (implicated donor withdrawn)</td></tr>
<tr><td>TACO</td><td>Sit up; O2; furosemide; slow future transfusion rate; smaller volumes; consider pre-transfusion furosemide for at-risk patients</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="products">Blood Products Overview</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Product</th><th>Indication</th><th>Key Points</th></tr>
<tr><td>Packed Red Blood Cells (PRBCs)</td><td>Anemia; blood loss; Hgb &lt;7 g/dL generally (&lt;8 in cardiac patients)</td><td>Each unit raises Hgb ~1 g/dL and Hct ~3%; infuse over 2&ndash;4 hr; requires crossmatch; type-specific preferred</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fresh Frozen Plasma (FFP)</td><td>Coagulopathy; reversal of warfarin when time-sensitive; multiple factor deficiency; DIC</td><td>Contains all clotting factors; ABO compatible (type-specific); thaw requires 20&ndash;30 min; must infuse within 24 hr of thaw; 10&ndash;15 mL/kg dose</td></tr>
<tr><td>Platelets</td><td>Thrombocytopenia (&lt;10,000 for spontaneous bleed risk; &lt;50,000 for invasive procedure; &lt;100,000 for neurosurgery); platelet dysfunction</td><td>Each unit raises platelet count by ~30,000&ndash;60,000; ABO preferred but not required; must agitate gently during storage; short 5-day shelf life; infuse over 30&ndash;60 min</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cryoprecipitate</td><td>Fibrinogen replacement; Hemophilia A (factor VIII); von Willebrand disease; DIC</td><td>Contains fibrinogen, Factor VIII, Factor XIII, vWF; 10-unit pool typically; infuse quickly</td></tr>
<tr><td>Albumin 5% / 25%</td><td>Hypovolemia; cirrhosis with SBP (25%); burns; nephrotic syndrome</td><td>5% = iso-oncotic (volume expansion); 25% = hyperoncotic (draws fluid from interstitium); no crossmatch needed; no disease transmission risk</td></tr>
</table>

<h2 id="nclex">NCLEX High-Yield Points</h2>
<ul>
<li>First action for ANY suspected reaction: STOP THE TRANSFUSION immediately; keep IV open with NS</li>
<li>AHTR hallmark = flank/back pain + dark urine (hemoglobinuria) = worst reaction; fatal without rapid intervention</li>
<li>TRALI = non-cardiogenic pulmonary edema (low CVP, bilateral infiltrates); NO diuretics; occurs within 6 hr</li>
<li>TACO = cardiogenic overload (HTN, high CVP); give diuretics; most common in elderly and cardiac patients</li>
<li>Mild allergic (urticaria ONLY, no fever) = give Benadryl; may restart after symptoms resolve</li>
<li>Only NS compatible with blood products; never dextrose or LR</li>
<li>Two licensed nurses must verify blood at bedside before transfusion</li>
<li>Transfuse within 4 hours of release from blood bank</li>
<li>Leukoreduced blood: prevents FNHTR and CMV transmission; indicated for immunocompromised patients</li>
</ul>

